The paper discusses decision-making in human-computer interfaces and online marketplaces, which involves exploring numerous alternatives of varying quality. This suggests that the paper could belong to the Game Theory (cs.GT) sub-category, which deals with decision-making in strategic situations. The paper also discusses the role of diversity in enhancing welfare, which could fall under the Social and Information Networks (cs.SI) sub-category, which deals with the study of social networks and their impact on information dissemination and decision-making. The paper also discusses the quality of consumed alternatives, which could fall under the Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-category, which deals with the study of algorithms that can learn from and make predictions on data. The paper also discusses search costs and decision-making, which could fall under the Information Retrieval (cs.IR) sub-category, which deals with the study of search engines and information retrieval systems. Finally, the paper discusses human-computer interfaces, which could fall under the Human-Computer Interaction (cs.HC) sub-category, which deals with the study of the interaction between humans and computers.
